The paper deals with the computation of an equilibrium concept in game theory, specifically the Extensive-Form Perfect Equilibrium (EFPE), which is a refinement of the Nash equilibrium. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also discusses the computational complexity of finding an EFPE, which involves solving a linear complementarity problem, and uses Lemke's algorithm, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also mentions the use of sequence form, which is a technique used in algorithmic game theory (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the presence of highly nonlinear constraints, which is a topic in optimization and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the application of the EFPE concept in realistic physical settings, which falls under the category of machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
